# PowerShell Shell Command Rules

When running shell commands on Windows (PowerShell), avoid piping git or other long-output commands through PowerShell cmdlets like `Select-Object`, `Where-Object`, etc. This can cause stream interruptions and connection errors.

## Use native tool flags instead

```bash
# BAD - PowerShell pipe can break the stream
git log --oneline | Select-Object -First 20
git show abc123 --stat --name-only | Select-Object -First 50

# GOOD - Use git's own flags to limit output
git log --oneline -20
git show abc123 --name-only --format=""
```

## General rules

- Prefer native command flags over PowerShell pipes for limiting/filtering output
- For `git log`, use `-n` or `-<number>` to limit results
- For `git show`, use `--name-only`, `--format=""`, `--stat` etc.
- For `git diff`, use `--stat` or path filters
- Avoid `head`, `tail`, `wc` — these are not available in PowerShell
- If you must filter output, prefer `rg` (ripgrep) over PowerShell cmdlets
